{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Graphs can be either linearized to SMILES strings (Edwards et al., 2022) (TYPE 2.C) or projected onto virtual tokens with graph encoders (Zhao et al., 2023a; Liu et al., 2023e) (TYPE 2.D).",
    "For instance, 3D-MoLM (Li et al., 2024c) uses a 3-dimensional molecular encoder to represent molecules as tokens and feeds them together with instructions into LLaMA-2 for molecule-totext retrieval and molecule captioning.",
    "Complementing text and graph modalities, molecular images form the vision modality in chemistry.",
    "Existing works adopt a similar philosophy to BLIP-2 (Li et al., 2023b), which represents each image as tokens and feeds them into an LLM (TYPE 2.D).",
    "For example, GIT-Mol (Liu et al., 2024a) projects all modalities, including graphs and images, into the latent text space and conducts encoding and decoding using T5 (Raffel et al., 2020)."
  ],
